# pyrst standard library — errno
#
# FIDELITY: 3.5/5 (see HARDENING note below — the original `errorcode` design
# did not compile; fixed to a function, which is a real syntax divergence)
#
# POSIX and Linux error codes as module-level integer constants, plus
# `errorcode(code)` — a function returning the symbolic name for a code
# (CPython's `errorcode` is a real dict; pyrst has no module-level dict
# state, see GATE HIT below).
#
# SURFACE:
#   - 133 symbolic error constants (EPERM, ENOENT, etc.)
#   - errorcode(code: int) -> str: symbolic-name lookup (130 valid codes,
#     keys 1..132 with two documented gaps at 41/58)
#
# GATE HIT (G2): CPython's `errorcode` is a module-level dict. pyrst has NO
# module-level mutable OR immutable dict/list/container state at all — the
# only legal top-level statement forms are `def`, `class`, `import`, and a
# bare-scalar-literal `NAME: T = <literal>` (`int`/`float`/`str`/`bool` only;
# see `src/typeck/checks.rs::is_const_literal`). A dict literal at module
# scope is a hard compile error ("top-level statements other than
# function/class/import ... are not supported"), so an "immutable const
# dict" is not an available design — it does not exist as a pyrst construct.
# RESOLUTION: `errorcode` is a FUNCTION, `errorcode(code: int) -> str`, that
# builds the table locally per call and indexes it — reusing the compiler's
# real dict-subscript KeyError codegen so a missing code still raises
# KeyError with the offending int, matching CPython's failure mode.
#
# DIVERGENCES:
#   - errorcode is a FUNCTION `errorcode(code)`, not a subscriptable dict
#     `errorcode[code]` (G2, see above). `.get()`, `len(errorcode)`, `in`,
#     and iteration over `errorcode` are NOT available — there is no dict
#     object to call them on. The lookup direction (code -> name) and the
#     KeyError-on-miss contract are preserved exactly.
#   - EAGAIN == EWOULDBLOCK (both = 11; errorcode(11) == 'EAGAIN')
#   - EDEADLK == EDEADLOCK (both = 35; errorcode(35) == 'EDEADLOCK', the
#     OTHER alias — verified live against CPython 3.12's real errno module;
#     an earlier draft had this backwards as 'EDEADLK', now fixed)
#   - ENOTSUP == EOPNOTSUPP (both = 95; errorcode(95) == 'ENOTSUP')

# Error Constants (133 items, all positive ints)
EPERM: int = 1
